{"source_key":"sha256-e5687aa6fc4c11d845e8d63e8ca8f175","record_index":180,"record_hash":"sha256:a025e5b6a5299308e1a970a7174d0d42fc0ec8a9c1d40bf84d141801dce5eb38","timestamp":"2026-06-04T11:32:05.855Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"I inspected `h5i-dev/h5i` read-only at commit `[REDACTED:entropy]`; no files edited.\\n\\n**1. What h5i Is For**\\nh5i is an AI-provenance sidecar for Git repos, not a Git replacement. Its pitch is “version control for the AI era”: record what agents were asked, what they read/changed, why decisions were made, what risks/tests existed, and carry that context through commits, PRs, agents, and clones via `refs/h5i/*` ([README.md]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\nThe concrete target use cases are production AI coding, reviewer provenance, long-running/multi-agent work, security/audit trails, reusable verified facts, and inherited AI-heavy repo triage ([README.md]([REDACTED:path])). Its strongest product wedge is reviewer/handoff workflow, especially PR summaries and “Agent Radio” typed handoffs, not just raw logging ([README.md]([REDACTED:path]), [README.md]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\n**2. How It Works Internally**\\nIt is a Rust CLI/server around Git. `H5iRepository::open` discovers the repo and ensures h5i layout ([repository.rs]([REDACTED:path])); the CLI is a Clap app with noun surfaces like `capture`, `recall`, `audit`, `share`, plus legacy verbs ([main.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [main.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\nStorage is split:\\n\\n- Local sidecar: `.git/.h5i/` for metadata, claims, memory, session logs, identities, read state, sync state, etc. ([storage.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [storage.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- Git refs: `refs/h5i/notes`, `refs/h5i/context/*`, `refs/h5i/ast`, `refs/h5i/memory`, `refs/h5i/msg` ([storage.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\n`h5i commit` creates a normal Git commit, then writes an `H5iCommitRecord` as a Git note under `refs/h5i/notes`; that record stores prompt/model/agent/test metrics/AST hashes/causal links/decisions ([repository.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [repository.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [metadata.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\nContext is a Git-ref-backed reasoning workspace. Each context branch lives under `refs/h5i/context/<name>` and stores `commit.md`, `trace.md`, `ephemeral.md`, `metadata.yaml`, and `dag.json` ([ctx.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [ctx.rs]([REDACTED:path])). It auto-follows Git branches unless pinned, and merges via real three-way Git-ish merges with append-only union behavior for trace files ([ctx.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [ctx.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [ctx.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\nAgent Radio stores structured messages in `refs/h5i/msg` as `messages.jsonl` plus `agents.json`; appends use a CAS loop, and read state is local per-agent seen IDs ([msg.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [msg.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [msg.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [msg.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\n**3. Main Capabilities**\\n- Capture provenance: `h5i capture commit` / `h5i commit` with prompt, model, agent, tests, decisions, AST, audit/policy flags ([main.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- Recall context: log/blame/diff plus context `show`, `relevant`, `search`, `smart`, DAG recap, pack, scope, todo, knowledge ([main.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [ctx.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- Share h5i refs: `share push/pull`, remote setup, legacy migration, PR body/comment generation ([main.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [main.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [pr.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- Typed messaging: `ask`, `review`, `risk`, `handoff`, `ack`, `done`, `decline`, [REDACTED:entropy] ([main.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- Integrations: GitHub PR comments via `gh` ([pr.rs]([REDACTED:path])), Codex session sync from `[REDACTED:path]` ([codex.rs]([REDACTED:path])), Claude hooks/log parsing ([session_log.rs]([REDACTED:path])), MCP over stdio ([mcp.rs]([REDACTED:path])), local Axum/React dashboard APIs ([server.rs]([REDACTED:path])), pytest/cargo test adapters ([h5i-pytest-adapter.py]([REDACTED:path]), [h5i-cargo-test-adapter.sh]([REDACTED:path])).\\n\\n**4. Limitations / Unknowns**\\n- It is not “just Git.” Important state remains local in `.git/.h5i`, especially claims, local read-state, identities, Codex sync state, pending context, and pre-push memory snapshots.\\n- Plain `git push` is not enough; users need `h5i share push/pull` or configured fetch refspecs for `refs/h5i/*` ([main.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- Claims appear local-only: stored as `.git/.h5i/claims/<id>.json`, with no obvious `refs/h5i/claims` sharing path ([claims.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- README storage docs are a bit stale: code uses `refs/h5i/context/*` and `refs/h5i/memory`, while the README table mentions older shapes ([README.md]([REDACTED:path]), [storage.rs]([REDACTED:path])).\\n- AST support looks narrow today; the parser path maps Python files to the bundled Python parser, not a broad multi-language semantic engine.\\n- Some commands mutate the working tree or config: `init`, hooks, memory restore, rewind/rollback/resolve. This is more than a passive log.\\n- I did not run the full test suite; this is code/docs/test inspection only.\\n\\n**5. Comparison-Relevant Facts**\\nFor contrasting with a git-native agent work log system, the real distinction is not “Git-backed vs not.” h5i is already Git-backed, but through sidecar refs plus local sidecar state.\\n\\nInference: h5i’s advantage is breadth: provenance notes, context DAGs, message protocol, PR summaries, dashboard, MCP, Claude/Codex/test integrations. It is closer to an AI development operations layer than a small work log.\\n\\nInference: a tighter git-native work log could compete by being simpler and more intrinsic to normal Git workflows: fewer hidden refs, fewer special push/pull commands, less local-only state, and a clearer mapping between agent activity and ordinary branch/commit history.\\n\\nThe sharpest contrast: h5i makes agent collaboration portable through `refs/h5i/*`, but it also creates a parallel world beside Git. A git-native agent log should probably win by making the work log feel like part of the repo’s actual history, not an extra protocol users must remember to sync.\"}}\n<[REDACTED:path]>","prompt_source":"system_injected","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-04T11:32:05.855Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}